        {
          "number": "455B.198",
          "heading": "Wastewater discharge from well drilling sites — rules",
          "body_text": "1.  The commission shall adopt rules pursuant to chapter 17A to regulate the discharge of wastewater from water well drilling sites. The rules shall incorporate the following considerations:\n  a.  The size of the well as measured by the flow of water in gallons per minute.\n  b.  The best management practices to address wastewater discharge.\n  c.  Requirements for notification to the department prior to the commencement of drilling operations.\n  d.  Requirements for retention of records for a well.\n  e.  Reasonable and appropriate limitations on wastewater discharge that take into consideration the need for the well.\n  f.  Reasonable and appropriate limitations on wastewater discharge that take into consideration the need to conserve soil and protect water quality.\n  2.  The commission shall have the authority in the rules to provide for the issuance of a general permit and to establish a fee sufficient to recover the costs of issuing a general permit, which shall not exceed fifty dollars. The fees shall be remitted to the department and shall be used by the department to administer the permitting requirements of this section.\n  3.  The commission shall convene an advisory committee that includes representatives of the Iowa water well association to assist in the development of the rules.\n;",
          "body_chars": 1310,
          "history_brackets": [],
          "acts_citations": [
            "2008 Acts, ch 1165, §1",
            "2015 Acts, ch 30, §132, 133"
          ],
          "referred_to_in": [],
          "citation_pdf_url": "https://www.legis.iowa.gov/docs/ico/section/2026/455B.198.pdf"
        },
        {
          "number": "455B.199",
          "heading": "Water resource restoration sponsor program",
          "body_text": "1.  The department shall establish and administer a water resource restoration sponsor program to assist in enhancing water quality in the state through the provision of financial assistance to communities for a variety of impairment-based, locally directed watershed projects.\n  2.  For purposes of this section, unless the context otherwise requires:\n  a.  “Qualified entity” means the same as defined in section 384.84.\n  b.  “Sponsor project” means a water resource restoration project as defined in section 384.80.\n  3.  Moneys in the water pollution control works revolving loan fund created in section 455B.295, and the drinking water facilities revolving loan fund created in section 455B.295, shall be used for the water resource restoration sponsor program. The department shall establish on an annual basis the percentage of moneys available for the sponsor program from the funds.\n  4.  The interest rate on the loan under the program for communities participating in a sponsor project shall be set at a level that requires the community to pay not more than the amount the community would have paid if they did not participate in a sponsor project.\n  5.  Not more than ninety percent of the projected interest payments on bonds issued under section 384.84 or the total cost of the sponsor project shall be advanced to the community, whichever is lower.\n  6.  A proposed sponsor project must be compatible with the goals of the water resource restoration sponsor program, shall include the application of best management practices for the primary purpose of water quality protection and improvement, and may include but not be limited to any of the following:\n  a.  Riparian buffer acquisition, enhancement, expansion, or restoration.\n  b.  Conservation easements.\n  c.  Riparian zone or wetland buffer extension or restoration.\n  d.  Wetland restoration in conjunction with an adjoining high-quality water resource.\n  e.  Stream bank stabilization and natural channel design techniques.\n  f.  In-stream habitat enhancements and dam removals.\n  g.  Practices related to water quality or water quality protection that are included in a field office technical guide published by the natural resources conservation service of the United States department of agriculture or are included in the Iowa stormwater management manual published by the department of natural resources.\n  7.  A proposed sponsor project shall not include any of the following:\n  a.  Passive recreation activities and trails including bike trails, playgrounds, soccer fields, picnic tables, and picnic grounds.\n  b.  Parking lots, unless a parking lot is constructed in a manner to improve water quality and construction is consistent with a field office technical guide published by the natural resources conservation service of the United States department of agriculture or the Iowa stormwater management manual published by the department of natural resources.\n  c.  Diverse habitat creation contrary to the botanical history of the area.\n  d.  Planting of nonnative plant species.\n  e.  Dredging.\n  f.  Supplemental environmental projects required as a part of a consent decree.\n  8.  A sponsor project must be approved by the department prior to participating in the water resource restoration sponsor program.\n  9.  A resolution by the city council must be approved and included as part of an application for the water resource restoration sponsor program. After approval of the project, the city council shall enter into an agreement pursuant to chapter 28E with the qualified entity who shall implement the project.\n  10.  A water resource restoration project shall not include the acquisition of property, an interest in property, or improvements to property through condemnation.\n  11.  The commission shall adopt rules pursuant to chapter 17A necessary for the administration of this section.\n; eferred to in §16.151, 455B.295, 461.34, 466B.44",
          "body_chars": 3936,
          "history_brackets": [],
          "acts_citations": [
            "2009 Acts, ch 72, §7",
            "2013 Acts, ch 53, §1, 2\nR"
          ],
          "referred_to_in": [
            "16.151",
            "455B.295",
            "461.34",
            "466B.44"
          ],
          "citation_pdf_url": "https://www.legis.iowa.gov/docs/ico/section/2026/455B.199.pdf"
        },
        {
          "number": "455B.199A",
          "heading": "Prioritization of municipal water quality improvement projects",
          "body_text": "1.  The department may allow schedules of compliance to be included in permits whenever authorized by federal law or regulations. Such schedules shall be established to maximize benefits and minimize local financial impact while improving water quality, where such opportunities arise. If information is provided showing that the anticipated costs of compliance with a schedule have no reasonable relationship to environmental or public health needs or benefits, or may result in other detrimental environmental impacts, such as significant greenhouse gas emissions, the projects may be deferred, in whole or in part as determined appropriate by the department, and a variance granted, as consistent with applicable federal law or regulations.\n  2.  Unless otherwise restricted by federal law or regulations, the department may allow compliance schedules of up to thirty years in national pollutant discharge elimination system permits, particularly where the costs of compliance with federal program mandates will adversely impact the construction of other necessary local capital improvement projects. If the department determines an existing condition constitutes a significant public health or environmental threat, the schedule of compliance shall be based on the shortest practicable time frame for remedying the condition.",
          "body_chars": 1329,
          "history_brackets": [],
          "acts_citations": [
            "2009 Acts, ch 72, §9"
          ],
          "referred_to_in": [],
          "citation_pdf_url": "https://www.legis.iowa.gov/docs/ico/section/2026/455B.199A.pdf"
        },
        {
          "number": "455B.199B",
          "heading": "Disadvantaged communities variance",
          "body_text": "1.  The department may provide for a variance of regulations pursuant to this part when it determines that regulations adopted pursuant to this part affect a disadvantaged community. Such a variance shall be consistent with federal rules and regulations. In considering an application for a variance, the department shall consider the substantial and widespread economic and social impact to the ratepayers and the affected community that may occur as a result of compliance with a federal regulation, a rule adopted by the department, or an order of the department pursuant to this part. In considering an application for a variance, the department shall take into account the rules adopted pursuant to this part with which a regulated entity and the commensurate affected community are required to comply.\n  2.  The department shall find that a regulated entity and the affected community are a disadvantaged community by evaluating all of the following:\n  a.  The ability of the regulated entity and the affected community to pay for a project based on the ratio of the total annual project costs per household to median household income.\n  b.  Median household income in the community and the unemployment rate of the county in which the community is located.\n  c.  The outstanding debt of the system and the bond rating of the community.\n  3.  The department shall find that an unsewered community is a disadvantaged community by evaluating all of the following:\n  a.  The ability of the community to pay for a project based on the ratio of the total annual project costs per household to median household income.\n  b.  The unemployment rate in the county where the community is located.\n  c.  The median household income of the community.\n  4.  The department shall not consider a regulated entity, affected community, or unsewered community a disadvantaged community if the ratio of compliance costs to median household income is below one percent.\n  5.  The department may grant a regulated entity a variance from complying with a rule adopted pursuant to this part or as otherwise allowed by federal law or regulations, if the department determines that the regulated entity or the affected community will suffer substantial and widespread economic and social impact. The department shall ensure the conditions of any variance improve water quality and represent reasonable progress toward complying with rules adopted pursuant to this part, but do not result in substantial and widespread economic and social impact.\n  6.  The department shall not require installation of a wastewater treatment system by an unsewered community if the department determines that such installation would create substantial and widespread economic and social impact.\n  7.  The Iowa finance authority, in cooperation with the department, shall utilize the disadvantaged community criteria in this section to determine the appropriate interest rates for loans awarded from the revolving loan funds created in sections 455B.291 through 455B.299, as allowed by federal law or regulations.\n  8.  The economic development authority shall utilize the disadvantaged community criteria in this section to determine eligibility for water or sewer community development block grants as provided in section 15.108, subsection 1, paragraph “a”.\n; ; eferred to in §16.134, 455B.199D",
          "body_chars": 3359,
          "history_brackets": [],
          "acts_citations": [
            "2009 Acts, ch 72, §10",
            "2011 Acts, ch 97, §6, 7",
            "2011 Acts, ch 118, §85, 89\nR"
          ],
          "referred_to_in": [
            "16.134",
            "455B.199D"
          ],
          "citation_pdf_url": "https://www.legis.iowa.gov/docs/ico/section/2026/455B.199B.pdf"
        },
        {
          "number": "455B.199C",
          "heading": "Alternative wastewater treatment technologies — legislative intent and purpose",
          "body_text": "1.  The intent of the general assembly is to address the rising costs of water and wastewater treatment compliance for regulated entities and affected communities by authorizing the use of alternative treatment technologies. The purpose of this section is to eliminate regulatory barriers that limit or prevent the use of new or innovative technologies.\n  2.  The department shall produce and publish design guidance documents for alternative wastewater treatment technologies. The guidance documents shall be intended to encourage regulated entities to use such technologies and to assist design engineers with the submission of projects employing alternative wastewater treatment technologies that can be readily approved by the department.\n  3.  In writing design guidance documents for alternative wastewater treatment technologies the department shall review all of the following:\n  a.  The on-site sewage design and reference manual published by the department of natural resources.\n  b.  The guidance manual for the management of on-site and decentralized wastewater systems published by the United States environmental protection agency.\n  c.  Other credible sources of information on the design, operation, and performance of alternative wastewater treatment technologies.\neferred to in §16.134",
          "body_chars": 1303,
          "history_brackets": [],
          "acts_citations": [
            "2009 Acts, ch 72, §11\nR"
          ],
          "referred_to_in": [
            "16.134"
          ],
          "citation_pdf_url": "https://www.legis.iowa.gov/docs/ico/section/2026/455B.199C.pdf"
        },
        {
          "number": "455B.199D",
          "heading": "At-risk utility systems",
          "body_text": "1.  For purposes of this section,“at-risk system” means a city drinking water, sanitary sewage, or storm water drainage system that the city determines meets any of the following criteria:\n  a.  The system serves a disadvantaged community as described in section 455B.199B.\n  b.  The system includes a water treatment plant, water distribution system, or wastewater treatment plant that has not been operated by a competent operator pursuant to section 455B.223 within the previous twelve months.\n  c.  The system violated one or more state or federal statutory or regulatory requirements in a manner that affects the safety, adequacy, or efficiency of its services or facilities.\n  2.  A new owner of an at-risk system following disposal of the system by sale pursuant to section 388.2A may provide to the department proof of the availability of financial resources to meet system upgrade requirements and a revised timetable for compliance with department rules. The department shall agree to the revised timetable if the department determines the revised timetable is reasonable based on the information provided by the new owner.\neferred to in §476.84",
          "body_chars": 1155,
          "history_brackets": [],
          "acts_citations": [
            "2020 Acts, ch 1095, §1\nR"
          ],
          "referred_to_in": [
            "476.84"
          ],
          "citation_pdf_url": "https://www.legis.iowa.gov/docs/ico/section/2026/455B.199D.pdf"
        },
