        {
          "number": "902.10",
          "heading": "Application for involuntary hospitalization",
          "body_text": "For the purposes of chapter 229, the director of the Iowa department of corrections is an interested person and all applicable provisions of chapter 229, relating to involuntary hospitalization, apply to persons who have been committed to the custody of the Iowa department of corrections as a result of a conviction of a public offense.\n\n83 Acts, ch 96, §132, 159",
          "body_chars": 364,
          "history_brackets": [
            "C79, 81, §902.10"
          ],
          "acts_citations": [],
          "referred_to_in": [],
          "citation_pdf_url": "https://www.legis.iowa.gov/docs/ico/section/2026/902.10.pdf"
        },
        {
          "number": "902.11",
          "heading": "Minimum sentence — eligibility of prior forcible felon for parole or work release",
          "body_text": "A person serving a sentence for conviction of a felony, who has a criminal record of one or more prior convictions for a forcible felony or a crime of a similar gravity in this or any other state, shall be denied parole or work release unless the person has served at least one-half of the maximum term of the defendant’s sentence. However, the mandatory sentence provided for by this section does not apply if either of the following apply:\n  1.  The sentences for the prior forcible felonies expired at least five years before the date of conviction for the present felony.\n  2.  The sentence being served is on a conviction for operating a motor vehicle while under the influence of alcohol or a drug under chapter 321J.\n88 Acts, ch 1091, §2; 96 Acts, ch 1151, §1, 2;",
          "body_chars": 770,
          "history_brackets": [],
          "acts_citations": [
            "2003 Acts, ch 156, §10"
          ],
          "referred_to_in": [],
          "citation_pdf_url": "https://www.legis.iowa.gov/docs/ico/section/2026/902.11.pdf"
        },
        {
          "number": "902.12",
          "heading": "Minimum sentence for certain felonies — eligibility for parole or work release",
          "body_text": "1.  A person serving a sentence for conviction of the following felonies, including a person serving a sentence for conviction of the following felonies prior to July 1, 2003, shall be denied parole or work release unless the person has served at least seven-tenths of the maximum term of the person’s sentence:\n  a.  Murder in the second degree in violation of section 707.3.\n  b.  Attempted murder in violation of section 707.11, except as provided in section 707.11, subsection 5.\n  c.  Sexual abuse in the second degree in violation of section 709.3.\n  d.  Kidnapping in the second degree in violation of section 710.3.\n  e.  Robbery in the second degree in violation of section 711.3, except as determined in subsection 4.\n  f.  Vehicular homicide in violation of section 707.6A, subsection 1 or 2, if the person was also convicted under section 321.261, subsection 4, based on the same facts or event that resulted in the conviction under section 707.6A, subsection 1 or 2.\n  g.  Continuous sexual abuse of a child in violation of section 709.23.\n  2.  A person serving a sentence for a conviction of child endangerment as defined in section 726.6, subsection 1, paragraph “b”, that is described and punishable under section 726.6, subsection 5, shall be denied parole or work release until the person has served between three-tenths and seven-tenths of the maximum term of the person’s sentence as determined under section 901.11, subsection 2.\n  3.  A person serving a sentence for a conviction for robbery in the first degree in violation of section 711.2 for a conviction that occurs on or after July 1, 2018, shall be denied parole or work release until the person has served between one-half and seven-tenths of the maximum term of the person’s sentence as determined under section 901.11, subsection 3.\n  4.  A person serving a sentence for a conviction for robbery in the second degree in violation of section 711.3 for a conviction that occurs on or after July 1, 2016, shall be denied parole or work release until the person has served between one-half and seven-tenths of the maximum term of the person’s sentence as determined under section 901.11, subsection 4.\n  5.  A person serving a sentence for a conviction for arson in the first degree in violation of section 712.2 that occurs on or after July 1, 2019, shall be denied parole or work release until the person has served between one-half and seven-tenths of the maximum term of the person’s sentence as determined under section 901.11, subsection 5.\n  6.  A person serving a sentence for a conviction of sexual exploitation of a minor in violation of section 728.12, subsection 1, shall be denied parole or work release until the person has served between one-half and seven-tenths of the maximum term of the person’s sentence as determined under section 901.11, subsection 6.\n  7.  A person serving a sentence for a conviction of human trafficking punishable as a class “B” felony in violation of section 710A.2, subsection 1, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, or 9, shall be denied parole or work release until the person has served between one-half and seven-tenths of the maximum term of the person’s sentence as determined under section 901.11, subsection 7.\n96 Acts, ch 1151, §3; 98 Acts, ch 1007, §1, 2; 98 Acts, ch 1088, §3; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; eferred to in §901.11, 903A.2, 904.301B, 904.911, 906.4, 906.15",
